        "text": "B−1 Consider the seven triples (a, b, c) with a, b, c ∈ {0, 1} not all zero. Notice that if rj, Sj, t j are not all even, then four of the sums arj + bsj + ct j with a, b, c ∈ {0, 1} are even and four are odd. Of course the sum with a = b = c = 0 is even, so at least four of the seven triples with a, b, c not all zero yield an odd sum. In other words, at least 4N of the tuples (a, b, c, j) yield odd sums. By the pigeonhole principle, there is a triple (a, b, c) for which at least 4N /7 of the sums are odd.",
