        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Since f is continuous, g is continuous where it is de- fined; but the set {1 + nπ/2k|n, k ∈ Z} is dense in the reals, and so g must be constant on its domain. Since g(−t) = −g(t) for all t, we must have g(t) = 0 when t is not a multiple of π. Hence f(x) = 0 for x ∈ (−1, 1). Finally, setting x = 0 and x = 1 in the given equation yields f (−1) = f (1) = 0.",
